.TH RUFUSARM64-CLI 1 "18 July 2026" "RufusArm64 0.11.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
rufusarm64-cli \- safely create bootable USB media on Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B rufusarm64-cli list
.RI [ --all ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli inspect
.BI --image " FILE"
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli hash
.RI [ --algorithm " md5|sha1|sha256|sha512" ] ...
.RI [ --all ]
.RI [ --json ]
.I FILE
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli write
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --device " /dev/DEVICE"
.RI [ options ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli write
.B --mode linux-persistent
.B --experimental-persistence
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --device " /dev/DEVICE"
.RI [ --persistence-size " SIZE" ]
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli uefi validate
.BI --directory " DIRECTORY"
.RI [ --arch " ARCH" ]
.RI [ --max-files " N" ]
.RI [ --require-fallback=true|false ]
.RI [ --dbx " FILE" | --firmware ]
.RI [ --sbat-level " FILE" | --firmware-sbat ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli uefi integrity manifest
.BI --directory " DIRECTORY"
.RI [ --max-files " N" ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli uefi integrity verify
.BI --directory " DIRECTORY"
.RI [ --max-files " N" ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli persistence plan
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --media-root " DIRECTORY"
.BI --target-size " SIZE"
.RI [ --size " SIZE" ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli persistence analyze
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --expected-source-identity " ID"
.BI --target-size " SIZE"
.RI [ --size " SIZE" ]
.RI [ --cancel-file " FILE" ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli qualify start
.BI --record " FILE"
.BI --output " FILE"
.RI [ --state-dir " DIRECTORY" ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli qualify verify
.BI --record " FILE"
.BI --output " FILE"
.RI [ --state-dir " DIRECTORY" ]
.RI [ --json ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B rufusarm64-cli
writes recognized GPT/MBR disk images and ISOHybrid Linux images directly, or
creates extracted Windows installation media. Windows media support GPT or MBR,
UEFI or x86-family BIOS/CSM, and Automatic, FAT32, or NTFS selection.
Compressed and common virtual-disk inputs are prepared before target erasure.
.PP
Version 0.10.5 supplies the engine used by the guarded graphical
persistent-live USB wizard. The single visible RufusArm64 application entry
opens the ordinary writer normally and exposes a Create Persistent Live USB
desktop action. The persistence path performs identity-bound read-only analysis,
exact target confirmation, fresh Polkit authorization, destructive creation
through a separate narrow helper, and post-creation qualification.
.SH IMAGE CHECKSUMS
.B hash
computes checksums from one identity-bound, already-open regular-file descriptor.
With no options it computes SHA-256 and retains the historical
.B sha256sum
compatible output used by existing scripts.
.PP
Repeat
.B --algorithm
with md5, sha1, sha256, or sha512 to select an ordered subset, or use
.B --all
to compute the stable Rufus-compatible four-algorithm set in one pass.
.B --json
emits the resolved path, file size, and ordered lowercase hexadecimal digests.
The command is unprivileged and responds to SIGINT and SIGTERM without opening a
block device or invoking Polkit. MD5 and SHA-1 are provided only to compare with
legacy published checksums; they are not used for trust, signatures, downloads,
or destructive-write assurance.
.SH UEFI MEDIA VALIDATION
.B uefi validate
performs a bounded, descriptor-rooted, read-only scan of a mounted or extracted
UEFI media tree. It validates the architecture fallback loader, PE machine and
EFI subsystem fields, bounded SBAT metadata, and optional DBX image-hash and
embedded-certificate revocations. It does not modify firmware or media.
.TP
.BI --directory " DIRECTORY"
Select the mounted or extracted media root. Every directory and EFI executable
is opened relative to a retained descriptor with no-follow semantics.
.TP
.BI --arch " ARCH"
Select native, 386, amd64, arm, arm64, riscv64, or loongarch64. Native is the
default.
.TP
.BI --max-files " N"
Set the bounded EFI executable count. The default is 512 and the library safety
maximum remains 4096.
.TP
.B --require-fallback=true|false
Require the architecture removable-media fallback loader. The default is true.
.TP
.BI --dbx " FILE"
Apply a local DBXUpdate.bin or raw EFI signature-list file.
.TP
.B --firmware
Apply the running firmware DBX instead of a local file.
.TP
.BI --sbat-level " FILE"
Apply a caller-trusted local shim-compatible SbatLevel CSV payload. A matching
image component is revoked only when its generation is lower than the trusted
minimum. The file is read once from a pinned regular-file descriptor.
.TP
.B --firmware-sbat
Use the SBAT level exposed by the running shim through efivarfs. The runtime
SbatLevelRT mirror is preferred and must have exact boot-service/runtime
attributes. A readable persistent SbatLevel fallback must have shim-compatible
boot-service/non-volatile attributes; readable copies must have identical
payloads. Firmware is never modified.
.PP
JSON output is emitted before an invalid-media failure status, allowing callers
to inspect the complete result while still relying on the process exit code.
.SH UEFI RUNTIME MEDIA INTEGRITY MANIFESTS
.B uefi integrity manifest
performs a descriptor-rooted read-only scan and writes exact uefi-md5sum-compatible
manifest text to standard output. It never writes the media tree. With
.B --json
it emits the same manifest text, total byte count, and ordered records in a
structured document.
.PP
.B uefi integrity verify
reads the exact root
.B md5sum.txt
and reports changed, missing, unexpected, and total-byte mismatches. JSON is
emitted before a non-zero invalid-media status. The default and maximum file
limit is 100000; manifest size is bounded to 64 MiB and paths to 512 bytes.
.PP
These commands are unprivileged. They do not mount images, open block devices,
invoke Polkit, access firmware, or install a bootloader. MD5 is used solely for
interoperability with the upstream boot-time validator; RufusArm64 continues to
use SHA-256 for source identity, downloads, and destructive-write assurance.
.SH COMMON WRITE OPTIONS
.TP
.B --verify
Flush block buffers and compare copied data after writing. Recommended.
.TP
.B --partition-scheme gpt|mbr
Choose the partition table for extracted Windows media. GPT is the default.
.TP
.B --target-system uefi|bios
Choose UEFI or legacy BIOS/UEFI-CSM. Windows ARM64 is UEFI-only.
.TP
.B --filesystem auto|fat32|ntfs
Choose the Windows-media filesystem. Automatic prefers FAT32 when safe and
otherwise selects NTFS. FAT32 can split oversized WIM/ESD payloads.
.TP
.BI --dbx-file " FILE"
Reject Windows EFI boot files revoked by the selected Secure Boot DBX. Firmware
is not modified.
.TP
.BI --driver-folder " DIRECTORY"
Validate and copy complete Windows driver packages for Windows PE and manual
Setup loading.
.TP
.B --full-format
Zero-write the complete new Windows data partition before formatting.
.TP
.B --bad-block-check
Zero-write and read back the complete new Windows data partition before formatting.
.TP
.B --yes
Skip interactive destructive-operation confirmation.
.TP
.B --allow-fixed
Permit a non-removable whole disk after all other safety checks pass.
.TP
.BI --expected-identity " TOKEN"
Require the target to match a refreshed token returned by the JSON list command.
The graphical workflows always supply this check.
.SH LINUX PERSISTENCE
.TP
.B --experimental-persistence
Enable the command-line GPT/UEFI persistent Linux writer. This flag is accepted
only with
.BR --mode " linux-persistent" .
The normal graphical writer still rejects this mode; the guarded persistence
wizard invokes its own package-owned helper. The wizard is opened from the
single RufusArm64 application entry or with
.BR "rufusarm64 --persistence" .
.TP
.BI --persistence-size " SIZE"
Set the ext4 persistence size using bytes or K/M/G/T units. Zero uses all suitable
aligned space remaining after the FAT32 boot partition. At least 1 GiB is required.
.PP
The initial compatibility scope is Ubuntu 20.04 or newer using casper and Debian
using live-boot. Ubuntu uses the
.B persistent
parameter and ext4 label
.BR casper-rw .
Debian uses
.BR persistence ,
ext4 label
.BR persistence ,
and a root
.B persistence.conf
containing
.BR / union .
.PP
Ubuntu detection accepts traditional kernel commands containing
.B boot=casper
and modern commands that select
.B /casper/vmlinuz
through a form such as:
.PP
.nf
linux /casper/vmlinuz $cmdline --- quiet splash
.fi
.PP
For the structural form, an unversioned image must also provide modern casper
metadata such as
.BR casper/install-sources.yaml .
The patcher inserts
.B persistent
before the
.B ---
separator, changes only family-matching kernel commands, rejects symbolic-link
paths, and re-detects the copied tree before success.
.PP
Read-only automatic analysis mounts only the identity-bound ISO and validates the
same complete media tree, architecture-matching fallback UEFI loader, FAT32 path
and file-size rules, boot-partition capacity, and requested persistence size used
by creation. It does not extend or rely on the ISO's embedded hybrid MBR geometry.
.PP
FAT32 cannot represent symbolic links. Bounded relative file and directory links
whose fully resolved targets remain inside the mounted image are materialized as
ordinary FAT32 entries, counted for capacity planning, hashed, copied, and rehashed.
Version 0.10.5 also recognizes a direct root-self alias such as the official
Ubuntu 26.04
.B ubuntu -> .
entry. That alias is omitted because materializing it would recursively duplicate
the complete image. Nested links back to the media root, absolute or external
links, cycles, device nodes, case collisions, oversized files, and unbounded
expansions are refused.
.PP
Persistent creation produces a fresh GPT with a FAT32 UEFI boot partition and an
ext4 persistence partition. It verifies both GPT copies, copies and rehashes a
bounded FAT32-compatible manifest, checks both filesystems, and flushes the target.
Compressed images, MBR/BIOS persistence, encrypted persistence, unknown layouts,
and files incompatible with FAT32 are refused.
.SH PERSISTENCE QUALIFICATION
.TP
.B qualify start --record FILE --output FILE [--state-dir DIRECTORY] [--json]
Verify the creation record and live environment, then store a private marker and
an initial JSON report with checksum sidecar.
.TP
.B qualify verify --record FILE --output FILE [--state-dir DIRECTORY] [--json]
After booting the same USB again, require a different Linux boot ID and the
surviving private marker, then write a verified report and checksum sidecar.
.PP
A passing result demonstrates persistence only for that observed reboot on the
exact image, USB, controller, firmware, and computer. It is not a universal boot
guarantee.
.SH SIGNED IMAGE ACQUISITION
.B acquire verify
and
.B acquire list
validate local detached Ed25519 catalogs before use.
.B acquire channel list
and
.B acquire channel download
use package-owned threshold-root metadata, rollback and expiry checks, verified
cache fallback, exact-size downloads, redirect-host limits, and SHA-256 checks.
The production built-in channel remains disabled until reviewed offline trust
metadata is provisioned.
.SH SAFETY
The program refuses partitions, read-only targets, the running root disk, and an
image stored on the selected target. It holds and hashes the selected source,
refreshes target identity immediately before destructive work, locks the target,
rejects unsafe symlinks, verifies bundled boot assets, flushes buffers, and checks
copied files and filesystems. Cancellation leaves incomplete media explicitly
unqualified.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Zero indicates success. A non-zero status indicates refusal, cancellation,
validation failure, I/O failure, filesystem failure, or verification mismatch.
